  "summary": "<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/26/what-happens-when-you-clone-a-mouse-for-58-generations.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"What happens when you clone a mouse for 58 generations?\"><img alt=\"Mouse (Rudmer Zwerver/shutterstock.com)\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"800\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/mouse.jpg?fit=1200%2C800&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"1200\" /></a><p>In 2005, a husband-and-wife team at Japan's RIKEN institute ran an experiment with a mouse: clone it, then clone the clone, then clone that clone, and keep going. Dr. Teruhiko Wakayama and Dr. Sayaka Wakayama kept it up for 20 years — through lab moves, a 2011 earthquake, and the pandemic — requiring 30,947 individual cloning attempts to produce 58 successive generations, <a href=\"https://denovo.substack.com/p/what-happens-when-you-clone-mice\">as summarized by Metacelsus</a>. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\" hr",
